which argument of print would you set for changing the default separator (space) ii printing the following line in current line
To change the default separator (space) when printing, you can use the sep argument in the print function.

For example, if you want to print the following line with a comma as the separator:

print('Hello', 'World', 'This', 'is', 'a', 'test')

You can use the sep argument like this:

print('Hello', 'World', 'This', 'is', 'a', 'test', sep=', ')

This will output:

Hello, World, This, is, a, test

If you want to print on the same line, you can use the end argument:

print('Hello', 'World', 'This', 'is', 'a', 'test', sep=', ', end='')

This will output:

Hello, World, This, is, a, test

Note that the end argument defaults to \n (newline), so setting it to an empty string ('') will prevent it from printing a newline at the end.
